  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I failed all technical interviews at Facebook, Google, Microsoft, Amazon and Apple. Should I give up the big companies and try some small startups?",
  "response": "I understand how discouraging it can be to face multiple rejections, especially from big tech companies. However, failing at these interviews does not necessarily mean giving up on your dreams or shifting your focus entirely. Here are a few suggestions to consider:\n\n1. **Reflect on your experiences**: Evaluate what might have gone wrong in these interviews. Identify specific areas where you struggled and try to address them. It could be your coding skills, system design knowledge, or interview techniques.\n\n2. **Skill improvement**: Use this opportunity to enhance your skills. There are several resources available online (such as LeetCode, HackerRank, and Coursera) that can help you prepare better. You can also consider taking specialized courses or certifications.\n\n3. **Mock interviews**: Participate in mock interviews with friends, mentors, or platforms like Pramp and Interviewing.io. This will help you get comfortable with the interview format and receive feedback.\n\n4. **Networking**: Connect with professionals in the industry through LinkedIn, conferences, and meetups. Sometimes, a recommendation can significantly boost your chances.\n\n5. **Startups and small companies**: Working at a smaller company or startup can provide valuable experience. You might have more responsibility, and the learning curve can be steeper, which could prepare you better for future interviews at big companies.\n\n6. **Persistence**: Don't give up on big companies if they are your dream workplaces. These companies often allow candidates to reapply after a certain period (usually 6-12 months). Use this time to strengthen your skills and come back stronger.\n\nRemember, setbacks are a part of the journey. Many successful individuals faced multiple rejections before achieving their goals. Stay positive, keep improving, and don't be afraid to explore different opportunities that can help you grow professionally.",
